otest movements, civil society organizations, and political parties. She shows us the different opportunities for economic and political participation that exist for them, explaining why young Egyptians may choose to either mobilize against or—surprisingly—in support of the regime. Sika underscores how youth in Egypt have been regarded as both the “hope of the nation” and a “threat to the nation.” Youth in Egypt shines a light on the rising generation of young people that represents Egypt's future and also has significant implications for the broader Middle East and North Africa region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aYouthzEgypt. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAl-Sisi.  aAuthoritarianism.  aCivic Engagement.  aCivic Participation.  aCivil Society Organizations.  aCivil Society.  aCo-optation Strategies.  aCo-optation.  aDepoliticization.  aDisengagement.  aEducation.  aEgypt Political History.  aEgypt.  aEmployment Opportunities.  aEntrepreneurship.  aGender.  aJanuary 25 Uprising.  aMENA.  aMarginalization.  aMedia.  aMobilization.  aMubarak.  aNasser.  aNeoliberalism.  aPolitical Economy.  aPolitical Engagement.  aPolitical Parties.  aPolitical Transitions.  aPoverty.  aRepression.  aRevolutionary Youth.  aYouth Contention.  aYouth Precarity.  aYouth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075163540uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479819577.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479819577423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479819577/original  a978-3-11-075163-5  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  